===Glyph origin 2===
Geometric variant of {{l|mul|𣦶}} and {{l|mul|⿱一𠂈}}, in turn from Tibetan letter {{l|bo|ཏ}} ([[#Chineserefs|Xu, 1944]]; [[#Chineserefs|Li, 1957]]; [[#Chineserefs|Qiu, 1988]]). 

Written as {{l|mul|⿱一𠂈}} in ''[https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?title=File%3ASibu_Congkan_Sanbian372-%E9%99%B6%E5%AE%97%E5%84%80-%E5%8D%97%E6%9D%91%E8%BC%9F%E8%80%95%E9%8C%84-8-1.djvu&page=38 Nancun Chuogeng Lu]'' [{{lang|mul|南村輟耕錄}}]; as {{l|mul|𣦶}} in ''[https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?title=File%3AHarvard_drs_17660186_%E6%AD%A3%E5%AD%97%E9%80%9A_v.17.pdf&page=21 Zhengzi Tong]'' [{{lang|mul|正字通}}]; and as {{lang|mul|歹}} in ''[https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?title=File:NLC892-411999031766-147248_%E9%87%8D%E8%A8%82%E7%9B%B4%E9%9F%B3%E7%AF%87_%E7%AC%AC3%E5%86%8A.pdf&page=50 Chongding Zhiyin Pian]'' [{{lang|mul|重訂直音篇}}] (cf. ibid.).

====Etymology 1====
{{zh-forms|alt=𣦶,䚟}}

From a Mongolian term ([[#Chineserefs|Xu, 1950]]; [[#Chineserefs|Li, 1957]]), identified as dayi- / dayin “enemy” (contemporary {{l|mn|дайн|ᠳᠠᠶᠢᠨ}} “war”); compare also the derived dayi*yi<!-- ⟨*y⟩ is a provisional placeholder for the handwritten letter in Junast (2005) to be identified--> “to rebel” ([[#Chineserefs|Junast, 2005]]).

Variously glossed with something containing the meaning “to rebel; to go against” or “bad” in Chinese historical documents. Curiously [https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?title=File:CNTS-00047692872_%E6%8C%87%E5%8D%97%E9%8C%84_-_%E5%B9%B7%E5%8F%8A%E7%B4%80%E5%B9%B4%E9%8C%84.pdf&page=75 ''Zhinan Lu''] ({{lang|zh|指南錄}}) glossed it using {{l|zh|奸細}}, meaning both “enemy agent” and “evil”, portending its semantic evolution.

